# Gentoo Optimizations

# The combination of xs, asm, orc, jit, threads, and kms represents a
# performance-oriented configuration that maximizes hardware utilization
# and system responsiveness. The asm, orc, and jit flags empower software to use
# hand-optimized assembly routines and just-in-time compilation, which
# significantly accelerates tasks like media processing and script execution. By
# including threads and kms, you ensure the system is optimized for multi-core
# parallelism and flicker-free, high-resolution graphics output via the kernel's
# display manager.
#
# -telemetry Disables upstream metrics tracking and background analytics
# reporting to maximize network privacy and eliminate data-collection overhead.
#
# TODO: removed seccom
# While you have explicitly excluded seccomp to prioritize stability and
# minimize overhead, this set of flags as a whole essentially forces your
# applications to run at the closest possible level to your underlying hardware,
# reducing software-induced latency.
*/* xs asm orc jit threads kms -telemetry

# The exclusion of nls (Native Language Support) is a deliberate choice to
# simplify the dependency graph and streamline the package installation process.
# By setting USE="-nls", you instruct Portage to ignore internationalization
# libraries and omit the compilation of localized message files, ensuring that
# all software interfaces default to English. This configuration is particularly
# beneficial on Gentoo because it prevents unnecessary interactions with the
# gettext utility and significantly reduces the total number of files installed
# across your system. Consequently, your updates will finish faster, and you
# will regain valuable disk space that would otherwise be occupied by dozens of
# translation files you do not need, resulting in a cleaner and more efficient
# OS environment.
#
# cjk: cjk (Chinese, Japanese, Korean), safe to disable globally.
#
# TODO
# icu: icu (International Components for Unicode). Do not disable globally.
# The icu library handles advanced Unicode data, character encodings, time/date
# formatting, and text collation. Unlike NLS, which just manages translations,
# ICU is a foundational component of modern text rendering and web engines.
# Consequences of disabling icu: Globally setting -icu will block the
# installation of software dependencies. Modern web browsers (Chromium,
# Firefox), desktop components, and typography libraries (such as
# media-libs/harfbuzz) require ICU. Forcing -icu will lead to severe dependency
# conflicts or build failures.
*/* -nls -cjk

# Remove bloat
*/* -debug -handbook -gtk-doc -doc -test -examples -accessibility -perl -firewalld -ppp -zeroconf -modemmanager

# Unless you use a physical Yubikey or hardware security token plugged into your
# machine for SSH authentication or disk decryption, disabling smartcard prevents
# system utilities from building smartcard-reading libraries
*/* -smartcard

# Fix modemmanager
# !!! The ebuild selected to satisfy
# ">=net-misc/networkmanager-1.10.4[introspection]" has unmet requirements. -
# net-misc/networkmanager-1.52.1::gentoo USE="bluetooth introspection nss
# policykit systemd tools wext wifi -audit -concheck -connection-sharing -debug
# -dhclient -dhcpcd (-elogind) -gnutls -gtk-doc -iptables -iwd -libedit
# -modemmanager -nftables -ofono -ovs -ppp -psl -resolvconf (-selinux) -syslog
# -teamd -test -vala" ABI_X86="(64) -32 (-x32)" The following REQUIRED_USE flag
# constraints are unsatisfied:
# bluetooth? ( modemmanager )
# The above constraints are a subset of the following complete expression:
# bluetooth? ( modemmanager ) connection-sharing? ( any-of ( iptables nftables )
# ) gtk-doc? ( introspection ) iwd? ( wifi ) test? ( tools ) vala? (
# introspection ) wext? ( wifi ) exactly-one-of ( gnutls nss ) at-most-one-of (
# elogind systemd ) at-most-one-of ( dhclient dhcpcd ) at-most-one-of ( syslog
# systemd )
net-misc/networkmanager modemmanager

# -xv (XVideo): This is an ancient, legacy X11 hardware video overlay path from
# the late 1990s. Modern video players render frames using OpenGL, Vulkan, or
# EGL directly onto the window surface. You do not need XV hooks.
*/* -xv

# Fix -zeroconf issue. An error occurs because the escl driver (Apple AirPrint /
# eSCL network scanning protocol) inside sane-backends requires network service
# discovery (zeroconf) to function. Because I have globally disabled zeroconf in
# my make.conf, disabling escl (-escl) is required.
media-gfx/sane-backends SANE_BACKENDS: -escl

# Make the GCC executable run faster when compiling other packages by building
# GCC itself using Profile-Guided Optimization (PGO) and Link-Time Optimization
# (LTO). This typically yields a 10% to 20% performance improvement in compile
# times.
sys-devel/gcc pgo lto

# PGO optimizes code blocks inside individual source files
app-shells/bash pgo
app-arch/xz-utils pgo
sys-devel/binutils pgo
dev-lang/python pgo

# Enables deduplication (deduplicate) to remove redundant, identical firmware
# files across different device folders, saving storage.
sys-kernel/linux-firmware deduplicate

# TODO removed tcmalloc lobally via USE flags can introduce build failures and
# runtime instability for packages that strictly expect the default glibc
# allocator. It is significantly safer to remove this from make.conf and apply
# it on a per-package basis via /etc/portage/package.use/.

# native-extensions: This flag influences how certain interpreted language
# packages compile performance-sensitive subroutines into native binary code.
*/* native-extensions
